-- Article 38: Benign Thyroid Diseases
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

MULTINODULAR GOITER (MNG): Most common cause of thyroid enlargement. May be non-toxic or toxic (Plummer disease). Presents as asymmetric thyroid enlargement with multiple palpable nodules. Complications include tracheal compression, dysphagia, hemorrhage into cyst, and malignancy (1-5%). Pemberton sign - facial plethora and JVD on arm elevation indicates retrosternal extension.

THYROID NODULES: Very common (4-7% palpable, 50% on ultrasound). Most are benign. Risk factors for malignancy include: age extremes, male sex, history of radiation, rapid growth, fixation, lymphadenopathy, family history of thyroid cancer or MEN syndrome.

EVALUATION: TSH first. If low TSH - thyroid scan (hot nodule rarely malignant). If normal or high TSH - ultrasound plus or minus FNAC. Ultrasound features suggesting malignancy: hypoechoic, microcalcifications, irregular margins, taller than wide, increased vascularity.'),
('d0000038-0000-0000-0000-000000000038'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Hyperthyroidism and Thyroiditis', 'GRAVES DISEASE: Autoimmune hyperthyroidism with TSH receptor antibodies. Features include diffuse goiter, ophthalmopathy, pretibial myxedema, acropachy. Treatment options: antithyroid drugs (carbimazole, propylthiouracil), radioactive iodine, or surgery. Thyroidectomy indicated for large goiter, ophthalmopathy, pregnancy planning, or patient preference.

TOXIC MULTINODULAR GOITER: Hyperthyroidism in elderly with MNG. No ophthalmopathy. Radioiodine uptake is patchy.

TOXIC ADENOMA: Single autonomous nodule producing excess thyroid hormone. Hot nodule on scan. Treat with surgery or radioiodine.

THYROIDITIS: Hashimoto (chronic lymphocytic) - autoimmune, may cause hypothyroidism, goitrous initially. De Quervain (subacute) - painful, viral, self-limiting. Riedel thyroiditis - rare, fibrosing, woody hard, may mimic carcinoma.

PREOPERATIVE PREPARATION: Patients must be euthyroid before surgery. Antithyroid drugs for 6-8 weeks. Lugol iodine for 10 days preoperatively reduces vascularity in Graves. Beta-blockers for symptom control.'),
('d0000038-0000-0000-0000-000000000038'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Surgical Management', 'INDICATIONS FOR THYROIDECTOMY: Compressive symptoms, suspected malignancy, cosmesis, hyperthyroidism refractory to medical therapy, retrosternal goiter, patient preference.

SURGICAL OPTIONS: Hemithyroidectomy (lobectomy plus isthmusectomy), subtotal thyroidectomy (rarely used now), near-total thyroidectomy, total thyroidectomy. For benign disease, hemithyroidectomy may suffice; bilateral disease requires total thyroidectomy.

COMPLICATIONS: Hemorrhage and airway compromise (emergency - open wound at bedside), recurrent laryngeal nerve injury (hoarseness - unilateral; stridor - bilateral), superior laryngeal nerve injury (voice fatigue, loss of high pitch), hypoparathyroidism (transient or permanent hypocalcemia), thyroid storm, wound infection, hypothyroidism.

RECURRENT LARYNGEAL NERVE: Runs in tracheoesophageal groove. Right nerve more variable, may be non-recurrent. Identify and preserve during dissection. Intraoperative nerve monitoring may be used.

PARATHYROID PRESERVATION: Usually 4 parathyroids. Preserve with blood supply or autotransplant if devascularized. Check calcium levels postoperatively.'),
('d0000038-0000-0000-0000-000000000038'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'TSH is the first test for thyroid nodule evaluation. Hot nodules on scan are rarely malignant. FNAC indicated for cold or ultrasound-suspicious nodules. Patients must be euthyroid before surgery. Lugol iodine reduces vascularity in Graves disease. Always identify RLN during surgery. Check calcium postoperatively - numbness and tingling may indicate hypocalcemia. Pemberton sign indicates retrosternal extension.'),
('d0000038-0000-0000-0000-000000000038'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'Multinodular goiter is the most common cause of thyroid enlargement. Malignancy risk factors: age extremes, male, radiation history, rapid growth, fixation. Graves disease: diffuse goiter with ophthalmopathy. Antithyroid drugs render patient euthyroid before surgery. Major complications: RLN injury, hypoparathyroidism, hemorrhage. Bleeding after thyroidectomy is an emergency - open wound at bedside. Check serum calcium postoperatively.');

